         <div type="comments">
            <p>
               <note type="remarks">Ogihara seems to suggest that the fragment preserves 4 lines of a 5-lines leaf (<bibl><title corresp="ref:ogihara2009">2009</title><citedRange>81</citedRange></bibl>). Indeed, line a1 was certainly preceded by another line, as was b4 followed by another; however, the leaf could also have had e.g. 7 lines, with my a1-4 being the original a3-5.</note>
               <note type="remarks">According to <bibl><title corresp="ref:broomhead1962"/><citedRange>88</citedRange></bibl>, "[w]ritten in medium ductus, and clearly preserved". A small fragment from near the Schnurloch of a large manuscript, four lines visible.</note>
               <note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment"><hi>pelai(kne)</hi>: on top of the <hi>pe</hi> there are three secondary inkspots.</note>
               <note corresp="#b1" type="lingcomment"><hi>eṅwe</hi> for <hi>eṅkwe</hi>.</note>
               <note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">Beginning of line: <bibl><title corresp="ref:ogihara2009"/><citedRange>81</citedRange></bibl> reads <hi>[_ṣ_ṣ_a]</hi>, but the reading is disturbed by a loose piece of paper (cf. also <hi>4</hi> in a4); therefore, his reading cannot be confirmed.</note>
            </p>
